  "prompt": "Why doesn't Wetransfer give the shared file links immediately on the screen after the upload completes, like SendSpace does?",
  "response": "WeTransfer\u2019s decision not to display the shared file links immediately on the screen after upload completion is likely intentional and aligns with its design philosophy and user experience strategy. Here are some possible reasons:\n\n1. **User Flow and Clarity**  \n   WeTransfer emphasizes simplicity and a clean interface. Providing the link immediately on the screen could clutter the interface or make the process feel less intuitive. Instead, it directs users to the next step (like entering an email) to ensure the link is shared correctly.\n\n2. **Email as the Primary Sharing Method**  \n   WeTransfer is designed to send files via email by default. Its core functionality revolves around notifying recipients via email rather than relying on manual link sharing. This approach ensures the recipient is directly informed and reduces the risk of the link getting lost or misused.\n\n3. **Security Considerations**  \n   By not displaying the link immediately, WeTransfer adds a layer of control. Users must actively request the link (e.g., by copying it from the email or accessing the transfer page), which can reduce the risk of accidental sharing or unauthorized access.\n\n4. **Encouraging Email Sharing**  \n   WeTransfer may prioritize email sharing because it\u2019s more controlled and traceable. It also aligns with their business model, as email sharing is a key part of their free and premium service offerings.\n\n5. **Branding and Experience**  \n   WeTransfer\u2019s design focuses on a smooth, guided experience. Immediate link display might disrupt this flow, especially for users who expect the email-first approach that WeTransfer is known for.\n\n6. **Differentiation from Competitors**  \n   WeTransfer\u2019s approach sets it apart from other file-sharing services like SendSpace, which may cater to users who prefer direct link sharing. WeTransfer\u2019s email-centric model appeals to users who want a seamless, hands-off sharing process.\n\nIn summary, WeTransfer\u2019s decision is likely tied to its user experience, security, and branding priorities, focusing on email as the primary means of sharing rather than immediate link display.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
